        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">It all depends on the zone and the # of HP's the mob you are fighting has.  There are some places you just can't fearkite (HS entrance anyone?).  Seafuries have a relatively low # of HP's than the mobs you will be fighting in a couple levels.</P><P>In Skyfire, I've been fighting (root/dot) wurms, wyrvens, and various other beasts out there.  My spells I use to kill them are:<BR>2 Splurts<BR>1 BoD<BR>2 Dooming Darkness<BR>1 Ebolt<BR>1 Plague<BR>2 - 4 Enstill's</P><P>Now, while the 2nd splurt will kill the mob's, if I want my health to be relatively high at the end of the fight I add another BoD.  When my 2nd BoD wears off, I'll be at 100% health and 50% mana.  Last night I tried some fear kiting there.  I used:<BR>1 Splurt<BR>1 BoD<BR>1 or 2 Dooming Darkness<BR>1 Ebolt<BR>2 fears</P><P>Fighting the same MoB's I would still do over 1/2 damage to get the exp (All of my Dot's finish).  I would finish 80% health or so and 80% mana and basically be ready for another fight.  The mob's also die faster, especially if you find yourself having to recast the same dot on multiple times.  By eliminating a Splurt, Plague, and BoD, that saves me about 850 mana (before specilization).  Granted the 2nd BoD is just for my heatlh, but if I don't use the 2nd Bod and my health gets too low while medding after battle, I have to turn lich off, then mana regen slows to a crawl.</P><P>The trick for fear kiting is determining how many spells you have to cast and still steal the exp from your pet.  Fear Kiting won't help if you cast the same amount of dots you would if you were root/dotting.</P><P>Wurtin</P><P>54th lvl Heretic of E'ci<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
