        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">There are times when you cannot use a pet, then root-dotting is the choice. But as soon i can make a pet, I do. Even when root-dotting. In case something goes wrong, you know. Most of the time, I try both and keep doing the most efficient one according to the situation. Sometimes, such as with Bloodgill gobs (very low HPs), I even find more efficient to nuke while pet is tanking (plus it raises my evocation skill). And I had use both tactics in one fight, like Gornit. I root-doted, then when root breaked, I fear-kited with pet and if Gornit went too close to cyclops, I root-doted again, calling pet back. Since you have to snare him anyway, ...<BR>But really the keys with pets are : it is safer, you have to do more DMG than it, it does a lot of damage for almost no mana. You just have to balance all this. When you find a way to allow your pet to do damage without it doing a lot of tanking or doing too much damage, it's a great victory for your mana bar, XP and down time.</P><P><BR> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

